Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:22.000
And I'm Georgie. For most parents, their babies first word is a special moment. This happens after an early stage of language development called Babel.

5
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
When babies start making simple sounds like Gah or Ma.

6
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Babies have to learn to use their mouth muscles to make specific sounds. They experiment with different sounds and mouth shapes.

7
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:40.000
So what exactly is happening when babies start learning to speak? What do you think, Georgie?

8
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Well, Phil, I'm no expert, but I imagine they watch the adults around them and kind of copy and imitate what they do, what do you think?

9
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
I definitely think that's what my children did when they were learning to speak.

10
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Let's compare our ideas with those of an expert.

11
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Professor Julian Pine from Liverpool University, speaking here on BBC Radio 4,

12
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.000
and he lists the skills that Babies develop in order to speak.

13
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Well, one of the first things the child's got to do is they've got to break down the speech stream into words.

14
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Then they've got to link the words to the things that they refer to in the environment, so they've got to learn what the word mean.

15
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Right.

16
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:27.000
In this program, we'll discover how Babies learn to speak, and as usual, we'll learn some useful new vocabulary.

