Some people find it helpful to study the vocabulary before listening.

19
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And another thing to do before listening is ask my question, Georgie, we've mentioned the babbling noises that Babies make when learning to speak,

20
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:56.000
but what age does this usually start? Is it a, around six months old?

21
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.000
B, around nine months old, or C, around one year old?

22
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Okay, I think my best guess would be a, around six months old.

23
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Okay, well, we'll find out a little bit later on in the program.

24
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Let's return to Professor Pines' list.

25
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:20.000
The first thing Babies do is recognize where individual words start and end.

26
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:27.000
For this, it helps to know that in English, at least words often begin with a stressed syllable.

27
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:33.000
The sound in a word which is emphasized by being spoken longer or louder.

28
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Learning this takes time and here, Professor Pines and Michael Rosen, presenter of BBC Radio Falls program, Word of mouth,

29
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
discuss children who haven't quite discovered it yet.

30
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:53.000
And we can see this in the kind of errors that children make, because little kids will often call the giraffe a wrath,

31
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
but leaving off the unstressed syllable because that's not typical English.

32
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Oh, and I've got an example of this. My sound used to call a machine a sming.

33
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
It just hit the stress. You didn't bother with the muppet.

34
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Yeah, exactly.

35
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Well, you may have thought it was my sming, of course. That's the other thing.

36
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:13.000
And the classic example, of course, is Narnar instead of banana.

37
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Yes, I think I call them that.

38
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:26.000
One error or mistake, infants make is calling a giraffe a wrath, because they cut off the first syllable G, because it's not stressed.

39
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:37.000
The classic example of this is when children say, Narnar instead of banana, a classic example of something means the best example of it.

40
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
One containing all the features you expect such a thing to have.

41
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
For example, ants are a classic example of animals working together.

42
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:53.000
The second skill babies develop as they learn to speak is correctly linking a word to the object it refers to.

43
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
In other words, knowing what the word means.

44
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:06.000
As adults, we do this without thinking, but it's actually much harder than it sounds, as Professor Julian Pine explains to BBC Radio for program, Word of mouth.

45
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Well, we take for granted the fact that it's kind of obvious what word refers to in the environment, but actually if you look at it from the child's point of view, it's really difficult to work out what a word refers to, because there's so many things it could refer to.

46
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
So, you know, the speech, signal is very ambiguous.

47
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:30.000
How does the child know that you're talking about the cup infant or the pen infant view when you say fan or cup?

48
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.000
As adults, we take it for granted that when a friend says apple, they mean that round red thing on the table.

49
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:43.000
To take it for granted, means to assume something without question.

50
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:53.000
But for a baby, the link between the word apple and the object is not obvious, it's ambiguous, meaning it has more than one possible meaning.

51
00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Wow, who knew so much was going on inside babies sponge like brains as they soak up the sounds they hear.

52
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Right, Phil, isn't it time to reveal the answer to your question?

53
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:11.000
It is indeed. The question was, at what age do babies start to make babbling noises?

54
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
And I said it was around six months.

55
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.000
And that is the correct answer.

56
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Yay!

57
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
Baby start to do this when they're about six months old.

58
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary that we've learnt starting with Babel, the meaningless noises babies make as they're learning to speak.

59
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:35.000
The stress syllable in a word is the sound which is emphasized by being longer, louder or higher.

60
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
An error is a mistake.

61
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:44.000
The classic example of something is the most typical example of it, containing its most important features.

62
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:50.000
If you take something for granted, you accept or assume it without question.

63
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
And finally, the adjective ambiguous means having more than one possible meaning.

64
